The paper discusses artificial neural networks and their ability to learn and generalise structural knowledge, which falls under the category of machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also draws inspiration from neuroscience and specifically focuses on the hippocampal-entorhinal system, which is related to computational neuroscience (cs.NE) and systems and control (cs.SY). The paper also discusses the emergence of spatial neuronal representations, which could be related to computer vision (cs.CV) or robotics (cs.RO). Finally, the paper discusses the use of entorhinal cell types as basis functions for constructing transition graphs, which could be related to computer communications (cs.CC).
